WEBVTT

1
00:00:11.790 --> 00:00:19.870
I am Kim Young-hee, working as a assistant at
Eminent Hospice for the past 6 months.

2
00:00:28.470 --> 00:00:34.310
My husband, who was usually sick, was discharged on
April 15th.

3
00:00:46.270 --> 00:00:51.950
I was able to stay at the hospital bed, wheelchair,
walker, oxygen heater, and

4
00:00:51.950 --> 00:00:57.630
other equipment provided by Eminent Hospice for the
past 1 month and 1 month.

5
00:00:57.630 --> 00:01:01.590
I was able to stay at the hospital bed safely and
comfortably without panic.

6
00:01:03.390 --> 00:01:07.425
I was also able to take the doctor who helped me at
the hospice

7
00:01:07.425 --> 00:01:09.730
a few days ago to the hospital bed.

8
00:01:12.030 --> 00:01:27.350
After a few days after he passed away, I began to
work from April 21.

9
00:01:36.100 --> 00:01:40.400
I worked as a nurse at Seoul National Hospital for
20 years.

10
00:02:06.440 --> 00:02:10.380
I worked as a nurse at a hospital bed to help my
baby father.

11
00:02:38.960 --> 00:02:40.360
Thanks to that, I am now working as a nurse at the
hospital bed.

12
00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:44.300
I am now helping those who need a hair cut or a foot
massage.

13
00:02:53.210 --> 00:02:59.850
I have been working for the first time since I was
born.

14
00:03:02.210 --> 00:03:05.310
I was 98 years old. I cried a lot for a long time.

15
00:03:07.110 --> 00:03:11.210
Before I went back to the hospital bed, I had to
change my diaper in the evening.

16
00:03:11.290 --> 00:03:13.670
My father was smiling at me with a wrong mouth.

17
00:03:16.290 --> 00:03:20.050
That night, my father was smiling at me like a
child.

18
00:03:22.910 --> 00:03:26.050
I thought that I should go and hug him.

19
00:03:28.750 --> 00:03:32.750
My heart ached a lot. He loved me.

20
00:03:38.050 --> 00:03:44.570
My mother is a Parkinson's patient, but she has a
lot of doubts.

21
00:03:45.310 --> 00:03:46.950
She was very scared of people she had never seen
before.

22
00:03:49.790 --> 00:03:52.290
She is very close to me now.

23
00:03:52.610 --> 00:03:54.030
I was also scared at first.

24
00:03:54.670 --> 00:03:57.450
She said she had never seen me before.

25
00:03:57.450 --> 00:03:58.370
She said she had never seen me before.

26
00:03:59.670 --> 00:04:01.630
She is a patient who can't move because her muscles
are paralyzed.

27
00:04:04.410 --> 00:04:07.630
She can't chew and swallow well.

28
00:04:08.790 --> 00:04:12.630
She can't express well because she can't speak well.

29
00:04:15.430 --> 00:04:18.890
But she is very close to me now.

30
00:04:19.290 --> 00:04:23.090
She sometimes gets depressed, but she is very happy
to communicate with me.

31
00:04:23.090 --> 00:04:27.870
When patients who are having a hard time because of
dementia, they also sympathize

32
00:04:27.870 --> 00:04:32.650
with their emotional state and say thank you when
they get used to it.

33
00:04:33.890 --> 00:04:46.830
It's very annoying. Therefore, I think it's most
rewarding when patients feel comforted and feel at ease

34
00:04:54.490 --> 00:04:57.610
I think most people don't know much about hospice
like my husband or my father.

35
00:05:00.850 --> 00:05:04.470
I think most people don't know much about hospice.

36
00:05:04.890 --> 00:05:08.650
I think there are many people who need help from my
experience.

37
00:05:12.670 --> 00:05:17.530
Please contact Eminot Hospice right now and receive
help.

38
00:05:19.350 --> 00:05:26.337
I'm trying to give as much help as possible to those
who need time

39
00:05:26.337 --> 00:05:29.830
and health to those who need it.

40
00:05:31.690 --> 00:05:33.250
Thank you.
